statement.p:
In the original paper in Aug, 1913 issue of Physical Reviews, R. A. Millikan, reported the readings on several drops. The data on one of the drops, Drop No. 6, is given below.

	 \amp \textrm{Radius of drop} = 2.76\:\mu\textrm{m};\ \ \textrm{Distance of fall or ascent} = 10.21\:\textrm{mm}
	 \amp \textrm{Electric potential across plates} = 5,085\:\textrm{V};\ \ \textrm{Plate separation} = 16\:\textrm{mm}
	 \amp \textrm{Density of oil} = 0.9199 \:\textrm{g/cm}^3;\ \ \textrm{Viscosity of air} = 1.824 \times10^{-5}\:\textrm{kg/m.s}
	 \amp \textrm{Averrage fall time in sec when E-field was off} = 11.88\:\textrm{sec}
	 \amp \textrm{Successive ascent times in sec when E-field was on:}
	 \amp \ \ \ 80.708,\ 22.375,\ 140.564,\ 79.600,\ 34.762,\ 137.308,
	 \amp \ \ \ 34.638,\ 22.268,\ 19.704,\ 77.630,\ 42.302.

From this data deduce the charge of the elementary charge by using the assumption used by Millikan: the difference in the rise times for the same drop when electric field is on is due to the charge difference among them, which would be due to the capture of loss of integral number of electrons.
